A fight pushed to the extreme: MP3 players against mobiles.
We will advise you, how to choose
While virtually all mobiles can play MP3 files, no MP3 player can phone.
It seems clear that it is better to buy only a phone.
Don’t let enough reasons exist to get an independent reader.
The choice depends entirely on the mode of use and the requirements of the future owner.
It would be absurd to buy for the home an expensive high-end phonograph to put on Maxim Turbulenc’s new album.
On the one hand, such musical products do not come out on vinyl disc, and, from a quality point of view, there is no objective reason for this to happen.
Now, if there’s in your shelves a lot of vinyl records, with rock art, jazz or blues, you’re probably dreaming of such a gramophone.
The same is true of music during travel, namely compressed music, to put it simply - from music to MP3.
There are also categories depending on the price and quality.
For one, it may be unacceptable to spend eight thousand crowns on a reader, in the same way a Pink Floyd fan would have trouble with hearing aids purchased for twenty crowns in the market.
Here are two extremes, among which there is enough room for everyone.
The choice is wide.
Battery life is also decisive
Some high-end music players are capable of much more than just playing music, but these are unknown features, of course, of most mobiles.
No current device is as universal as the phone.
In addition to the first functions, phone calls and SMS sending, it is able to play music and movies, record the latter, it has a camera of varying quality and can, for example, be used for navigation.
And if you take into account smartphones and communicators, you will have a small computer in your pocket.
Since no refrigerator knows how to grill meat and no TV will take photographs, we are virtually witnessing a miracle.
However, the universal character of mobile is not without drawbacks.
The larger the number of functions you use, the smaller the interval between two recharges will be.
And playing music is one of the most important energy bubbles.
Rare are the mobiles that are able to play music for ten to twelve hours, in most cases, this figure is considerably lower.
In this regard, music players (especially the most rudimentary) are significantly more performers.
In the case of cheap mobiles, count on them to play music only for a few hours.
If, in addition, you can call from time to time, make sure, to be sure, a second charger for work - this is even valid for more expensive devices.
The problem will not arise for MP3 players, which are capable, following a recharge, of a continuous operation of at least 9 hours, including the least performing.
Another problem occurs when recording music on your mobile.
Unfortunately, a limited part of the devices have a universal USB connector, especially since not all can be directly connected to the computer, without special software.
Music can, of course, be recorded directly on the memory card, but few card readers know how to take it without reduction, given the small dimensions of the memory cards used in mobile devices.
As for the drives, you do not need any software, except for the exception (iPod).
Simply fill in, through the USB connector, the music device coming from the computer.
Most mobile phones and readers will create their own media library sorted by the name of the interpreter, the title of the album, the style, or at the discretion of the user.
Some devices display only an index with a tree structure, like Windows Explorer, others are capable of both (iriver, Samsung, Sony, Cowon, smartphones with operating system).
Readers are easier to handle, mobiles have more know-how
In choosing a concrete device, you are especially interested in the life of the accumulator, the capacity of the memory, the quality and the type of sound output and, of course, the ease of control.
If the music is for you, essentially, a background noise and if in the day you are going to listen to it only for a limited time, for example by taking the tram, you just need any mobile playing the MP3s.
Almost all mobile devices are capable of doing so today.
You don’t even have to pay too much attention to the music formats that the mobile or the player is capable of playing.
Everyone can play MP3s and the vast majority of the music that will come to you will have just this format.
It is one of the most common formats and apart from it, the vast majority of devices can also play music in WMA format.
The AAC (format used by Apple and its iPods) is less common.
High-end mobiles also allow, for example, to buy music online.
Just visit, from the mobile phone, the corresponding operator’s (or other provider’s) web pages and buy the song or album in question.
This service alone should be a compelling reason to get a musical mobile.
The offer of the operators is unfortunately miserable and is, in most cases, limited to quick-made radio tubes.
The prices are also not the lowest.
However, it is generally considered that this way of buying music (whether through GSM, Internet, or even wireless internet) will dominate the music industry in the future.
Most people always wear their mobile phones on themselves.
Every time you want to listen to something, you just have to get the mobile out of your pocket, while you’ve forgotten your MP3 player at home.
However, it is also important if you still have headphones on or a handsfree with connection.
If this is not the case, you can use the built-in speakers, which have virtually all mobile phones, but a minimum of MP3 players.
For many, the main advantage of musical mobile is their price.
The cheapest ones usually cost less than 3,000.
For a price of three or four thousand crowns, you can have a very convenient walkman already.
But in most cases, you will be limited by the lack of output for regular headphones.
The price of the best phones and the best tools, also provided with an input for ordinary headphones, does not exceed fifteen thousand.
Readers, on the other hand, have the advantage of having an easy command.
Indeed, anyone can ensure the order of the most rudimentary readers - which do not necessarily correspond to the least expensive (see our choice).
A minimum of functions; and the similarity of the command with that of a cassette station, commonly used in the past, or a gramophone, is obvious.
There is no risk of collision in the form of a randomly connected mobile internet, followed by a huge data transmission bill.
Which device to choose
Even the cheapest mobiles (e.g. the Vodafone 527) usually have a slot for interchangeable memory cards (type M2, microSD, and so on).
Even taking into account the additional purchase of such a card, you will not exceed two thousand crowns.
But be careful.
Basic models generally only support cards with a maximum capacity of 2 GB.
Only the most expensive ones come out even with 8 GB memory cards.
If you already own a mobile and still want to buy a cheap MP3 player, take a Cowon, a Creative, a Sony, a Samsung, a Emgeton, or an iriver.
Depending on the capacity (max. 2 GB), you should not spend more than 1,100 crowns.
If you are one of the most demanding listeners, instead choose specialized walkman mobiles (Sony Ericsson, some Nokia and Samsung).
These devices are equipped with independent control keys for MP3, and so the ease of the control approaches that of an independent MP3 player.
Sony Ericsson, whose mobiles in the Walkman series have the same user menu as MP3 players sold separately, is the one that went the most far in this area.
The same service, in the same price category, but with a memory capacity (up to 16 GB) and a longer battery life (usually 15 hours, up to 35 hours), is provided by an MP3 player produced by one of the above brands.
A first virtual operator will win the Czech Republic this year.
Possibly
The mobile market in the Czech Republic is relatively advanced, with our operators offering virtually the same services as their Western European partners.
Despite this, we still lack something - a virtual operator, which would force the classic operators to lower prices.
It may not be missing for a long time.
We have already mentioned, on several occasions, on Mobil.cz the fact that Czech operators are among the most expensive in Europe.
The <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A> (Czech Telecommunications Office), which reported that the price of an SMS was higher in our country than in the rest of the Union, confirmed it.
Thus, following the European Commission's last steps in the field of the regulation of roaming fees, a paradoxical situation is likely to occur - SMS sent from abroad will be cheaper for some customers of Czech mobile operators than in the country.
How is it possible that prices in the Czech Republic remain so high, compared to Europe?
The answer is simple, there is a lack of competition that would really want to enter the fight.
This may seem paradoxical, since we still have three mobile networks and a penetration that far exceeds 100%.
On the contrary, mobile operators like to complain that the Czech market is extremely competitive.
In this case, Pavel Dvo<0xC5><0x99>ák, the Chairman of the Council of the Czech Telecommunications Office (<0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A>), who has repeatedly stated that in the Czech Republic there is no room for another operator, choruses with the operators.
It’s probably true that a classic operator with its own network apparently doesn’t have much luck anymore (by the way, now it’s hard to find frequencies).
But there is still a possibility - a virtual operator.
It is precisely the entry of virtual operators into the mobile market that has led to a considerable drop in prices, to which they would subsequently have to react as well.
Yet even before disturbances such as Tesco Mobile or Virgin Mobile entered the market, voices similar to those we hear today at home were heard in the UK.
But it turned out that there was still room for such operators and that they could have a real success.
We are not obliged to go too far to find examples.
In February we informed you about the launch of the virtual operator Mobilking in Poland.
In just six months, this operator has managed to win more than 100,000 customers and become the fifth operator in the country.
Let’s add that behind Mobilking, there is the financial group Penta, which owns the U:fon in the Czech Republic, among others.
The advantage of virtual operators is the ability to focus on a much more concrete target group.
In order for their operation to be efficient, they need much less customers than a conventional operator.
They are, in fact, exempt from the relatively high costs of construction, operation and maintenance of the mobile network.
This is how virtual operators around the world profile themselves as low-cost operators – they offer cheap calls and SMS, which is often counterbalanced by a limited service offering.
For example, Tesco Mobile offers SMS in the UK at least twice as cheap as its competitors.
However, as the example of Mobilking in Poland shows, betting on an unusual target group can also be a good advertising hit.
In fact, this operator is specifically aimed at men.
“Real men choose Mobilking – an operator they like and can trust,” says David Seibert, CEO of Mobile Entertainment Company, who operates this virtual operator.
It is difficult to say, if such a concept would be likely to work in our home as well.
Vodafone spokesman Miroslav <0xC4><0x8C>epick<0xC3><0xBD> said: “The Czech market is relatively small for a segmental approach, on which most virtual operators are based.
Especially since it is relatively saturated from the point of view of the service offering."
In the Czech Republic, no chance, say mobile operators
However, it seems almost certain that if there is a virtual operator in the Czech Republic, it will not be Mobilking.
"We are discussing the expansion of this successful project, but in the Czech Republic the negotiations are not very encouraging.
The launch of Mobilking will rather take place in other countries in our area," said Jana Studni<0xC4><0x8D>ková, a spokeswoman for Penta Financial Group, in a telephone interview for Mobil.cz.
It thus indirectly confirmed that the operators in the Czech Republic were, at any rate, not in favour of this idea.
On the contrary, they try to do their best so that a potential competitor may not appear.
GTS Nowera Group, which would like to take a new step to become a real competitor of Telefónica in the corporate customer sector, has not hidden, for quite a long time, its intention to launch a virtual mobile operator.
“We want to be able to offer our customers not only fixed telecommunications services, but also mobile.
And the sooner it will be the best.
We have already negotiated this possibility on several occasions with all Czech mobile operators.
With some, we managed to move forward in the negotiations,” said Group spokesman Pavel Kaidl.
Perhaps the future is promising.
According to non-official information, it seems that we might be able to host the first virtual operator by the end of the year.
But for the moment, his creation is accompanied by total silence.
“At the moment, we do not believe that there is room in the Czech market for a virtual operator as such.
The Czech market is very specific compared to others.
So far, no subject with a complex and serious project in this area has contacted us," said Vlastimil Sr<0xC5><0xA1>e<0xC5><0x88> of the Telefónica O2 press department, in his statement to Mobil.cz.
Other operators also refer to the specificity of the Czech market.
T-Mobile spokeswoman Martina Kemrová said in a rare agreement with O2's statement: "We have not recorded for the moment a viable and bilaterally advantageous project, which could serve as a basis."
She added: “It is virtually excluded that a virtual operator will appear in the T-Mobile network by the end of the year.
In order to operate in such a limited period of time, we should now have a concrete agreement."
Vodafone instead focuses on fulfilling requests to obtain its own 3G license.
Miroslav <0xC4><0x8C>epick<0xC3><0xBD> says: “We are open to negotiations with potential virtual operators, especially in the field of shared costs and infrastructure.
This is what we believe means the most input from the point of view of customers.
Vodafone’s main strategy in this area is the discovery of a partner to establish a common network for fast mobile internet.”
Responsible authorities: in phase with operators
The approach of mobile operators is easily understandable, the entry of another operator would mean an increase in competition, would have led to a decrease in prices and therefore to a decrease in their profit.
What good is it to facilitate the advent of such a competitor?
When it comes to their interests, the operators can hear each other like a fair. The chicane accompanying the creation of the U:fon also bears witness to it.
The largest apparent pressure on the <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A>, when U:fon was created, was that exerted by T-Mobile.
This is evidenced by information accessible to the public from the <0xC4><0x8C>TU web pages.
Nowadays, U:fon is ready to serve as an argument to not accept a virtual operator.
Martina Kemrová commented: "Mobile market competition has also recently been amplified by the entry into the market of a fourth mobile operator.
Given the nature of the mobile market in RT, it is obvious that the entry of an additional player would subject it, and especially its services, to high demands."
But given the attitude of the mobile operators, the indifference of the Czech regulatory bodies seems to be confounding.
However, this is not just the attitude of the <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A>, which, unlike Britain and other developed countries, unfortunately, does not have the power to intervene in economic competition in the Czech Republic.
It belongs exclusively to the Office for the Protection of Economic Competition (OECD).
However, the latter adopted, in the face of this problem, its typical position.
"The entry of a virtual operator into the mobile market would be possible as a result of the conclusion of an agreement between a mobile operator and the virtual operator concerned regarding the lease of the necessary infrastructure.
No such agreement has been concluded at the moment, as the offer of potential stakeholders has not a priori presented sufficient interest to the classic operators," said in response to our question Kristian Chalupa of the <0xC3><0x9A>OHS Department of Foreign Relations.
A statement thus made would not be surprising on the part of operator representatives.
But on the part of an office, which must represent the interests of consumers and, among other things, take care to ensure that no one benefits from its position on the market, such a statement is more than disturbing.
As Kristián Chalupa adds, “Overall, where virtual operators are normally present, it can be seen that their entry into the market has contributed to a decrease in the prices of mobile phone services.”
However, pressuring for a fair functioning of the market and a price drop is apparently not part of the interests of the <0xC3><0x9A>OHS.
What is really shocking is the almost touching concord of the three mobile operators, which results from their reactions.
The question, if this is really a coincidence, comes naturally.
Similarly, a price of gasoline strictly identical to all gas stations is probably due to chance and fierce competition.
"The agency has not detected any signs of anti-competitive behaviour in this regard, so it has no reason to intervene in one way or another.
None of the operators has a dominant position, and none therefore has an increased corresponding responsibility for their market behaviour.
The tools needed to open the mobile market to virtual operators are probably missing even the telecommunications regulator," Chaloupa said in a statement.
The interpretation of the dominant position on the market is one of many points of disagreement.
Of course, there is an analysis of the relevant markets developed by the <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A>, according to which telecommunications constitute, from the point of view of economic competition, a single market.
None of the Czech operators has a dominant position in such a market.
However, some legal experts propose a different view of things: for the creation of a virtual operator to be possible, it is necessary to obtain, each time, the consent of the network operator.
And the mobile operator logically has the monopoly on its network.
This is how it necessarily plays a dominant role in a certain segment of its activity.
However, even without admitting this argument, it should be at least troubling for the <0xC3><0x9A>OHS that three mobile operators are visibly acting in a similar manner.
However, the complaints of many interested parties (including GTS Novera, already mentioned) show that they face similar constraints in negotiations with all operators.
Taking responsibility back on the <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A> is a fairly common thread in communications, whereby the <0xC3><0x9A>OHS washes its hands of the case.
We have encountered this type of attitude in a number of similar cases.
Unfortunately, the recent renewal of the Telecommunications Act did not bring about an enlargement of the <0xC4><0x8C>TU's powers in the field of economic competition in telecommunications, although many specialists promised an improvement in the situation.
The representatives of the <0xC3><0x9A>OHS must know this very well, but their interests are apparently elsewhere.
When no one looks, it can work.
That said, the operation of a kind of pseudo-virtual operator, several in Czech mobile networks, remains unnoticed.
These are companies that publish their own price lists for mobile phone services, but these are only partially public.
In most cases, it is a question of multi-level marketing companies.
For example, personalized mobile phone services are offered by Amway, Bohemia Telecom, Starlife and many others.
The price lists of these firms usually only reach voters.
The magic tower consists in the fact that the company does in front of the operator figure of a classic business client, who orders a large amount of SIM cards.
As an important customer, she gets special price (and other) offers.
The problem is that the trade conditions of all Czech mobile operators prohibit such a resale.
"If what you are referring to happened, it could be a breach of the contractual terms that we would examine and which could result in a termination of the collaboration with the company in question," said Martina Kemrová.
However, it is quite unlikely that an echo of such an activity did not reach the responsible mobile operators.
Especially in the case of the three companies mentioned, it can be thousands of customers.
None of the operators, however, is against such a procedure.
Indeed, the activities of these firms bring them non-negotiable profits, and at the same time, unlike real virtual operators, they do not threaten them at all with their own official marketing.
Miroslav <0xC4><0x8C>epick<0xC3><0xBD> points out the possible problems: "The law allows such speculation, however, the services of these companies are used only by a negligible percentage of customers.
In addition, they are forced to admit that the SIM card in their phone is not registered under their name, so they cannot fully dispose of it, in the manner of ordinary customers of mobile operators."
But that is exactly what should seem strange to the <0xC4><0x8C>TU.
In addition, another question is asked at the <0xC3><0x9A>OHS.
If mobile operators close their eyes on such a procedure, why are they blocking the creation of a virtual operator?
It should be added that the <0xC3><0x9A>OHS has relatively broad powers to be able to disclose such an activity, and if it does not wish to be content with the explanations of the operators, who claim to have no idea that this would happen, their contractual terms prohibit it.
When we will no longer be the most expensive country
As we have already mentioned on several occasions, the entry of virtual operators into the mobile market has brought about a considerable reduction in the price of services.
Now, in virtually all countries where virtual operators appeared, classic operators were trying, sometimes more, sometimes less, to prevent their creation.
The arguments used by the latter were virtually the same - a market too small, or even too saturated, problems with the quality of services, etc.
It is precisely at this level that the regulatory bodies in the developed countries have intervened, which did not defend the interests of the mobile operators, but those of their customers.
Both by formal measures and by informal pressure, they eventually obtained the creation of a first virtual operator, followed by others.
Unfortunately, the Czech regulators are dealing with this issue in the same way as a hot potato, which can be disposed of by sending it to a nearby target.
Following the experiences we have, we can only get rid of the impression that the confusion in their skills is more than profitable in these cases.
But don't throw the handle after the cognac.
If the background information is true and a virtual operator will appear soon at us, the Czech mobile market may be back on the move.
If one of the operators has accepted the creation of a virtual mobile operator, the <0xC3><0x9A>OHS will hardly be able to remain impatient in the face of the rejection (discrimination) of other stakeholders.
And perhaps we will stop calling more expensive than in the rest of Europe.
