Olmert would return almost all occupied territories in exchange for peace.
Ehud Olmert, the President of the Israeli Provisional Government, spoke in favour of the restitution of virtually all occupied territories in 1967, including the West Bank, East Jerusalem and the Golan Heights, in exchange for peace with Palestine and Syria.
He made this statement in an interview published Monday by the newspaper Yedioth Ahronoth.
“We have to reach an agreement with the Palestinians, which means it will be necessary to return almost all (occupied) territories, or even all,” Olmert said.
“We will keep a certain percentage of the territory, but we will have to give the Palestinians an analogous percentage (of the Israeli territory), since without it, peace will not be done,” he added.
He admits that the possible restitution would include East Jerusalem.
"He who desires security in Jerusalem, and most of all does not want tractors and bulldozers to crush his feet, as it happened to one of my best friends, will have to give up parts of Jerusalem," Olmert noted, referring to the two people in the city, who were attacked by several people, and who were killed by several bulldozers.
According to the Prime Minister, it will be necessary to find "a special solution for the Temple Mount, the sacred and historic places" located inside the Old Town.
“Anyone who wants to maintain Israeli sovereignty over the entire city will be forced to integrate 270,000 Arabs.
It won't work," he said later.
Retreat of the Golan Heights
Olmert also expressed his support for Israel's retreat from the Golan Heights, which he believes is an indispensable condition for the conclusion of a peace agreement with Syria.
However, this would also require some effort on the part of Damascus.
"I do not propose to conclude peace with Syria only on the basis of a Golan retirement," he said.
“The Syrians know very well what they will have to give up to get the Golan.
They will have to give up their current relations with Iran; they will have to give up their relationship with Hezbollah (the Shia movement); they will have to give up the constant support they give to terrorism by Hamas (the Shia movement), al-Qaeda (the former terrorist network of the Islamic State), and the former leader of the Islamic State.
Questions that arise after the accident: Are the stewards in the car illegal?
The law ignores them; walking in a long distance is forbidden.
In the context of the tragic bus accident of the Student Agency company near Padua, Italy, the question arises whether the stewards and passengers can move within the bus during the journey.
“If we wanted to comply with the law in a strict and formal way, the activity of a steward is contrary to the Road Traffic Act,” said Transport Ministry spokesman Karel Hanzelka.
The accident in question, during which a 22-year-old hostess died, was apparently caused by the driver of a truck that crossed the bus road.
The young girl was unfortunately sitting next to the driver, on the most dangerous seat of the vehicle, although she had two other seats at her disposal.
However, the bus may have an accident, or even a sudden braking, even when the steward serves the coffee or distributes the newspapers.
What matters is whether the bus is under its technical sheet equipped with standing seats or not.
If this standing-seat equipment is not approved, passengers must remain seated.
The long-distance Student Agency buses do not have standing seats; which was confirmed in Aktualn<0xC4><0x9B>.cz by the director of the company Radim Jan<0xC4><0x8D>ura.
“This is an issue that we have dealt with with with the ministry and, in the beginning, it banned any travel of passengers.
Then they canceled it and we got that passengers can go to the toilet during the trip provided they have their own seat," he said.
The law ignores the stewards.
"There is no unambiguous legal interpretation of the role of steward - no legal requirement is concerned with that role.
On the other hand, no legal requirement prohibits the carrier from offering services.
The Road Transport Act only knows the term of vehicle receiver; it does not define its rights and duties,” added the spokesman, Hanzelka.
Josef Pokorn<0xC3><0xBD>, the Director of the Department of Road Vehicle Traffic, believes, on the contrary, that the law adequately addresses the issue.
“It all depends on whether the bus has permission to offer standing seats in its approval.
Everything is in there," he said.
Buses are divided into urban, where there are standing seats and a limited maximum speed, interurban with standing seats and a higher permissible speed, and long-distance buses without a standing position with the highest permissible speed and seats equipped with seat belts.
As in the plane, an expert said.
Jaroslav Ho<0xC5><0x99>ín, an expert at BESIP (Road Traffic Safety) in Transportation, does not see the movement of stewards on board as a major problem.
"With regular traffic, there is no danger. The situation can be compared to that of the service in aircraft.
There too, it is not certain when turbulence will occur and the hostess of the air may shake her head."
Or, in the event that the bus suddenly braked, the laws of physics would obviously be valid.
In the same way as in an urban bus or in a tram.
The carrier must manage the security of the stewards by internal regulations," he says and also believes that from the point of view of the law, the issue is not resolved.
Jan<0xC4><0x8D>ura is ready to remove these services
Student Agency is the only bus carrier to offer steward services.
He hired two hundred.
Even after this accident, the director does not consider their profession as a risky profession.
"However, as soon as I have the impression that this is a risky profession, I will delete it.
Passengers can receive their coffee and newspapers on board.
This would also reduce costs,” he said.
The safety concern is the reason given to the absence of stewards in his vehicles by the director of the Asiana Alexei Litvine, who ensures, in comparison with SA, a very small number of lines.
"We don't have hostesses, we've been opposed to this since the beginning.
Sooner or later it will end in a deadly accident," he said, a year ago, at T<0xC3><0xBD>den.cz.
A huge tragedy has come.
A young hostess from the Plze<0xC5><0x88> region, who had worked for the company for two years, died in the accident on the Naples line.
A Slovenian truck probably left the emergency stopping strip without using a flashlight and blocked the road to the bus.
The driver of the latter tried to avoid it by means of a sudden maneuver, but he rolled it on his right side.
Jan<0xC4><0x8D>ura denied that the two seats reserved for the stewards were sold.
"In the case of long-distance lines, it is not possible to book these seats, they are blocked."
The company intends to file a complaint against the truck driver.
For the compensation of the girl's family, the agency will not wait for the judgement of the court, but in terms of financial compensation, it also counts on the culprit.
An amendment to the law?
Not in view
An amendment to the law, which has been being drafted for more than a year by a group of thirty experts from the Ministry of Transport, could provide clarification on the movements of the stewards on board the bus.
"Or, she has not reached any conclusions on this point.
In fact, she is not too interested in buses, but rather in the point system, the maximum speed on the highway and the use of the laptop at the steering wheel," says expert Ho<0xC5><0x99>ín.
"The Department of Transportation does not consider the activity of the stewards as something that would fundamentally jeopardize the safety of passengers," said Hanzelka, stating that the control of the safety of buses is under the control of the police and the Occupational Safety Office.
The hopes of Düsseldorf rest on Frankfurt.
The big words were not lacking in the letter from the WestLB Board of Directors to the House employees.
By joining the entities of the Düsseldorf financial institution with the Deka-Bank of Frankfurt, "the central financial market institution of the Sparkasse financial group" could constitute itself, according to the mail released on Monday.
The WestLB would bring a "competence block" doubled with sustainable productivity in such a case.
Overall, such a relationship could be a decisive move towards other concentrations in the Länder banking sector.
This is what it looks like when a steering committee wants to demonstrate its ability to act in difficult times.
Because the WestLB, wounded, is always under strong pressure.
It is not only the European Commission, but also the Federal Financial Services Surveillance Authority that has, only recently, made it clear to the Government of the Land of North Rhine-Westphalia that time was counting in the search for a future solution.
However, it has been questioning for some time already - also on the Frankfurt side - a relationship of any form between the bank Deka, which knows the customers of the Sparkasse by their investment funds, and the WestLB.
It is certain that Deta-Bank chief Franz Waas announced during the presentation of the figures for the end of August that he saw no sense in the merger of the Mainzer Landstrasse house with a Land bank, whether it be the Helaba or the WestLB.
However, the Board of Directors of the Deka, each half of which is supported by the banks of the Länder and by the savings box groups, commissioned the Steering Committee to conduct discussions with the WestLB for joint business activities.
It could then be the debt of the financial market, or parts of it.
The talks, however, have only just begun, it is said in the financial place.
This is not the first time that Deta-Bank, with its 3,000 employees, is one of the most important employers in Frankfurt’s financial place, and is at stake in the consolidation of the savings box sector.
In 2003, it was believed for a while that Deta-Bank could merge with Land Rhineland-Palatinate and Halbab Bank.
However, nothing has emerged from this ternary bouquet.
The plans had hardly been made public that the government of the Land of Hesse was against any Hellaba participation in them.
Later, the other two houses also did not join.
The Land Bank of Rhineland Palatinate was attached to the Land Bank of Baden-Wuttenberg in Stuttgart.
But there have always been new treaties on the regrouping of the Deka-Bank with banks from Länder.
Lastly, however, Günther Merl, chairman of the Hellaba Board of Directors, had decided against any merger strategy with his bank.
In spite of this, there seems to be a widespread feeling that the grouping of the various public sector institutions is particularly urgent.
Now that the elections to the Land of Bavaria Parliament have passed, a union of BayernLB with the Land of Baden-Wuttenberg bank could be achieved first and foremost.
For Helaba, this is not particularly good news.
If the pressure for further mergers was to increase, potential partners would gradually escape it.
In the South, it would now be a junior partner, although it has so far resisted the crisis better than the banks of Munich and Stuttgart.
Hesse-Thuringe, which holds 85 percent of Helaba’s capital, has, on the other hand, closed its entire alliance with the WestLB at the beginning of the year.
The NordLB would remain strict.
Such geo-strategic reflections, however, reflect only one of the facets.
Another aspect raises the question of how the different business models of each of these banks can fit together.
In June, Merl stated that the decisive question, namely, by which business model the future capacity of the Länder banks should be ensured, had not been resolved so far by the German grouping of savings and transfers.
In the end, a WestLb disembarkation could take place, disembarkation which is obviously not desired here.
This is also the case in the letter of the current Steering Committee: in any case, a 'global solution' for the establishment would be aimed at.
How all this will be put in the same basket with the union of certain entities with the Deta-Bank remains to be seen.
