Nights of Insomnia for Hypo Real Estate Shareholders
The German banking system is relatively stable, the Federal Finance Minister insisted just a few weeks ago.
What a chance the politician used the word 'relatively' and slipped that the German banking sector would not be spared by the crisis movements.
This has actually happened this weekend.
Bavaria real estate financer Hypo Real Estate (HRE), alongside the DAX, gets a <0x24>1 billion loan from a consortium of German banks to protect itself from market turbulence.
A person in confidence of the situation told Reuters on Monday that aid credits were issued up to a sum of <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>35 billion.
The Hipo Real Estate is now expected to pay interest on the fraction to which it would thus be entitled.
The money comes from both private and public banks.
In the background, it is the Deffa subsidiary that bears the losses.
According to a newspaper article, the state financer had refinanced himself in the very short term for long-term projects for which he had borrowed money - which is no longer possible since mistrust of markets.
In the first half of 2008, the bank's liquidity reserve had been reduced from 95 per cent to EUR 2.37 million, and the equity rate had also slightly decreased from 1.6 per cent to 1.45 per cent.
The current and net profits from financial transactions fell to zero compared with the same period the previous year, the profits from the allocation of fixed liabilities and securities as well as the termination of provisions in credit transactions had dropped from more than 5 million to 70 million.
And it is only thanks to the significant profits derived from the reimbursement of downstream accounting costs from the restructuring of the former Depfa Group, as well as the reimbursement of interest according to the book of tax procedures and commercial purchases for Konzern companies that the deficit of earnings is about 16 percent.
After its privatization in 1990, the former state financer had initially misspent on industrial real estate credits, which had then been affiliated with Aareal Bank.
Due to the insufficient profitability of conventional state funding, Depfa has subsequently been more involved in infrastructure projects and in joint projects between private and state investors (Privat-Public-Partnership, PPP) and diversified internationally.
On the value of the subsidiary, the Hypo Real Estate must make amortizations that should have on the calculation of the group's gains and losses an essential material effect that remains quite blurred nonetheless.
The fact is that the dividends were amputated.
As of 2007, they had been reduced to two-thirds.
Since the acquisition of Depfa, Hypo Real Estate has been a very important state and infrastructure investor.
It is more robust than other institutions dependent on refinancing in the interbank market since it does not have any customer deposits.
With the bankruptcy of investment bank Lehman Brothers two weeks ago, the allocation of loans between banks has risen again considerably, with banks accumulating their liquidity.
The Hypo Real Estate needs an annual share of Depfa’s total credits of a short-term refinancing medium – about 50 billion euros.
According to a statement from the Hypo Real Estate, the group’s financing needs are covered with medium-term credit and the company protected from the influence of international financial markets largely out of the current state of play.
Other sources say that refinancing would be provided through the funds until the end of 2009.
On the other hand, HRE’s chairman, Georg Funke, explained that the Hypo Real Estate group should no longer have recourse to medium-term financial markets.
The Federal Bank and the Federal Financial Services Surveillance Institute (Bafin) are based on the principle that the capacity of the Hypo Real Group in the market is now secured.
The bank’s shareholders and creditors have nothing to do with it.
However, given the dynamics and impossibility of the crisis, there is no certainty.
Moreover, it is not unthinkable that funding should not be used in its entirety.
But the opposite cannot also be discarded.
After the bank is, according to the latest reports, still on the doorstep of insolvency on Sunday evening, this at least temporary rescue will not be able to reassure the spirits either.
The price of the share fell from 75 percent to 3.30 euros.
Bond prices, on the other hand, are particularly good.
While the debts to the first boss have barely moved, the prices of the second-floor loans are floating.
The most affected are the investment funds of the former Württemberg Hypo subsidiary and of course those that have a lifespan beyond 2009.
Hypo Real Estate bonds used to appear to be an alternative speculation investment, but now their value has to be seen as dependent on the stability of the international banking system after the net hardening of the banking crisis and the crisis of the institution itself that brought the crisis into the establishment by the buyout bank.
As long as issuing institutions, governments and less affected commercial banks are still ready to support the system, it can be assumed to re-absorb downturns over time.
Or it will happen what no one dares hope at this time - that the financial crisis can be overcome in the next 15 months.
But in the face of the renewed noises of partial nationalization, the probability that security was approaching has now become a mere grounded hope.
This should reserve nights of insomnia first and foremost to long-term creditors on the decision of whether they should separate from their commitments.
Short-term investors can still use what they have drawn on to constitute a loss postponement for the upcoming years on the upcoming capital gains tax automatically collected.
