Rats also have sensations.
A rat or a coward flees from danger, does that mean that he is also afraid?
The neurophysicist Joseph LeDoux is convinced of this: many animals also have sensations.
But how can we verify that he feels the same when he behaves the same way we do?
In the online magazine "Edge", contributions have been published for several years by famous scientists.
SPIEGEL ONLINE presents in a series of articles the answers to the question "What do you think is true without being able to prove it?"
I believe that animals have sensations and other states of consciousness without me or anyone else having been able to prove it so far just as one cannot prove that other human beings have consciousness.
But in that case, we can at least hope that all human brains have the same configuration.
As soon as we turn to other species and address the issues of feeling or consciousness in general, we penetrate hard-to-practice terrain because the Hardware does not match.
When a rat is in front of a danger, it does the same thing as many other animals: it kills, escapes or attacks.
Humans behave the same way, which is why some scientists deduce a comparable subjective life.
However, I don't believe it.
Two aspects of the structure of the brain make it difficult to transpose our subjective life into that of animals.
One aspect is that circuits almost always associated with human consciousness include the prefrontal lateral cortex (due to its participation in short-term memory and management and execution functions).
This vast region is much more developed in humans than in other primates and appears to be completely absent in other beings.
Therefore, at least for these aspects of our consciousness that depend on the prefrontal cortex, including the consciousness of who we are, and the ability to predict and decide, it is reasonable to assume that human beings differ even from other primates.
Another significant peculiarity could reside in the linguistic nature of man: much of his existence being linked to language, this often means that his consciousness depends on it.
In this case, animals could be excluded.
But even if consciousness should not depend on language, it would certainly influence it, so that animal consciousness, no matter how it is produced, would probably differ greatly from most of our states of consciousness.
This is why it is so difficult to determine what consciousness can look like in other animals.
If this, internally and subjectively, is neither measured nor, because of this particular Hardware, analyzed on the basis of our own experience, then its observation poses great problems to us.
Most of my developments refer to the content of conscious living, but there is another aspect of consciousness that should be more readily accessible scientifically.
Animal consciousness processes could be examined without taking into account their contents, and this is exactly what happened during studies on the short-term memory of primates, especially with the example of visualization.
But in this approach followed by Christof Koch and Francis Crick, we focus more on the nervous correlations of consciousness than on the causal mechanisms: both can be identical or not.
Interestingly, this approach also highlights the weight of the prefrontal cortex in the realization of visualization.
But what does it mean for the emotions?
I conclude that an emotional system such as the fear system is activated in a brain that is aware of its own activity.
What we call “fear” is therefore the mental state in which we find ourselves when the activity of the defense system located in the brain (or its consequences, such as the body’s reactions) captures living memory.
Thus observed, emotions are closely related to the regions of the cortex that characterize primates and especially humans.
Subtle degrees of feeling, associated with our voluminous nature, are released, because we can, with the help of words and grammar, differentiate and categorize states to imput them to others than ourselves.
On the contrary, Antonio Damasio, for example, thinks that sensations from primitive activities are born in the areas of the body sensation of the cortex and brain trunk, as well as Jaak Pankseep who, however, focuses more on the brain trunk.
Since this network has not changed much over the course of human evolution, it could fully participate in transversal sensations of all kinds.
From a purely theoretical point of view, I cannot contradict it, but I believe it is indescribable.
Pankseep argues that what appears as fear in both men and rats is probably as felt as such in both cases: how could one check whether rats and men feel the same when they behave similarly?
A coward runs away from danger, but what if he feels afraid?
In my view, similar behaviors are not enough to prove identical experiences.
Of course, the nervous comparison helps: rats and humans have similar brain trunks, but cats don’t even have a brain.
But is the brain trunk the cause of the sensations?
And even if we could prove this to man, how could we prove it in rats?
I think rats and other mammals, maybe even cockroaches (who knows?) have sensations.
But I wouldn't know how to prove it.
And because their sensations are probably completely different from ours (because human consciousness is based on special circuits and language), I prefer to explore the emotional behavior rather than the emotional sensations of rats.
In any case, progress is made on the nerve level as the same is measured in rats and in humans.
Since I don’t explore language and consciousness in rats, nor sensations, I don’t know if they exist.
It could be judged as short-term, but I prefer to move forward rather than constantly crawling against a wall.
I am a pragmatic emotional.
