Talking and Sleeping
Some children talk during the night.
I am not referring to those who wake up very awake by telling us something that happened the day before, but to the children who speak during their sleep.
The first time it happens it may surprise you, but in reality it doesn’t matter.
It is a benign alteration of sleep that is called somnolence.
This is quite common, especially in children and adolescents.
I'm sure there's more than one who talks during the night.
This phenomenon can occur very sporadically (once in life, for example, associated with an episode of severe fever), or more periodically (every day, once a week, once a month...), the day after the child remembers nothing.
There is no single cause that determines its appearance.
They are often associated with other sleep disorders such as nightmares, night terrors, night drowsiness (picking in bed) or sleep apnea, but this is not always the case.
As we have already said before, they can also be associated with very strong fevers, stress or overexcitation situations.
Either way, it is a phenomenon that has not been studied.
The intensity with which it occurs is also very variable.
It may be that he speaks with a quiet little voice, with isolated words, murmurs or on the contrary with screams, tears, long speeches...
In the case of somnolence becoming very common, it would be wise to observe the child and consult a specialist, to check if there is a problem that causes a lot of anxiety and in order to get an explanation for this problem.
We said it is a benign alteration, which is why there is no treatment, unless it is related to another sleep disorder that can be treated (for example, if it is related to sleep apnea or stress).
What can be done is to take into account a number of very simple preventive measures such as:
Try not to excite the child before going to bed.
Therefore, look for quiet games and avoid programs or TV series that are more or less violent.
With children who are very nervous and hard to relax, relaxation techniques can be used to help them calm down internally.
This will allow the child to have a more peaceful sleep.
As soon as the dreams appear, try to stay calm.
Remember that they are harmless to the child and that the next day he will no longer remember what happened.
Useful Tips
Don't wake him up.
It's useless because he's unconscious and you'll wake him up.
Even if he talks, he sleeps and rests.
Remember that if he is very anxious several times, it is advisable to consult a doctor or check what causes so much anxiety in the child.
If you understand what he says (which is not usual), don’t be tempted to question him for information.
You won't get anything, because sleeping, he's not conscious to be able to organize his thought.
In addition, you will hear what he says, but you will not know what he is dreaming about, so pay attention to how you interpret the information and the conclusions you draw.
Never tell the child that you can question him during the night to know his secrets.
Not even jokingly.
This causes a lot of anxiety.
In conclusion, don’t worry, it’s not a good thing, it’s an episode that only lasts a few minutes.
