The Interview - From the Blood Became Safe
Hema-Québec celebrated the 10th anniversary of its founding yesterday, and its president, Dr. Francine Décary, was right to be glad, as Hema-Québec has become one of the safest and most effective blood suppliers in the world.
And above all, he regained public confidence, which had been severely shaken by the blood-contaminated scandal in the 1980s and 1990s.
As is well known, national blood reserves managed by the Canadian Red Cross Transfusion Service were contaminated with the acquired immunodeficiency virus (HIV) and hepatitis C virus during the 1980s.
In February 1994, the Government of Canada instituted a public investigation, chaired by Judge Horace Krever, which aimed to shed light on the circumstances that led to such a tragedy and to make recommendations to prevent such a disaster from occurring.
While Judge Krever was delayed in filing his report, some provinces then set up a committee aimed at planning a new blood management system in Canada.
In Quebec, the Gélineau Committee has fulfilled this mandate.
Following the Gelineau and Krever reports, two suppliers were established in Canada: Hema-Québec to serve Quebec and the Canadian Blood Society to supply all other provinces and both territories.
“In 1998, when Hema-Québec began its operations, only 38% of people still had confidence in the blood system in Quebec,” recalls Dr. Décary.
The situation was discouraging.
As a result of efforts to improve the safety of blood products and work on the ground over the following years, we regained public confidence,” she said before proudly affirming that by the beginning of 2008, nearly 94 percent of the Québec population now had confidence in Héma-Québec.
However, Dr. Décary keeps in mind that “trust is something extremely fragile.”
Since its inception on 28 September 1998, Hema-Québec has applied the precautionary principle.
At that time, Europe witnessed the eclosion of many cases of the human form of mad cow disease, a new variant of Creutzfeldt-Jakob’s disease, which has been strong since its foundation in 1998.
"And we didn't know at all if this disease could be transmitted through blood.
We then relied on one of the main recommendations of the Krever and Gelineau reports, according to which when it is not known and a serious disease can result from it, in the case of Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, which is characterized by a degeneration of the brain, which leads to the inevitability of the dead.
In April 1999, therefore, the blood of people who had been in the UK for more than a month since 1980 was refused.
Now, a few years ago, it has been demonstrated undoubtedly that this disease is transmitted through the blood.
This episode thus showed us that the precautionary principle that was applied made sense."
In 1999, a much more sensitive HIV screening technique appeared on the market: nucleic acid tests (TANs) that allow donors to detect directly in the blood the presence of the virus itself and not the presence of antibodies against the virus, on which the tests used so far relied.
TANs have shortened the silent period, which extends between the time the person was infected and the time when the first viruses can be detected in the blood by our techniques, the specialist explains.
This period could be reduced to a duration of less than one week.
This significantly reduced the risk that some donors would be infected without knowing it and could not be detected.
These improvements have significantly reduced the risk of contracting AIDS by blood transfusion.
Today, one in 12 million people are at risk of receiving HIV-contaminated blood.
In other words, it means that 12 million blood products will need to be distributed before someone is infected with HIV.
As Hema-Québec distributes between 400,000 and 500,000 blood products each year, it will take more than 24 years before a case of HIV transmission occurs with a blood product.
I believe that today one can feel comfortable receiving or prescribing a blood transfusion to recover health,” says the chief executive of Hema-Québec.
“Our challenge for the next decade is to maintain the safety of our products.
It is never known which pathogen will emerge in the system.
Not later than last year the Chikungunya virus appeared on the island of Reunion, which, like the West Nile virus, is transmitted by an insect in the blood.
We need to be constantly vigilant," continues Dr. Décary, stressing that in addition to a secure supply, Hema-Québec must also provide for adequate supply.
“Needs are increasing because the population is getting older.
As anticancer treatments are more aggressive, patients often need red blood cell or platelet recharge.
The ageing of the population also has consequences for the blood donor network, which averages only 3% of Quebecers eligible for blood donation."
Any healthy person aged 18 and over who meets the eligibility criteria can donate blood every 56 days, or six times a year.
On average, 14% of people who offer their blood are not accepted because they are infected with AIDS or malaria, for example, and if they have traveled to a country where malaria is severe, they will be excluded for a period of one year.
“With these 3%, we are able to maintain an inventory that meets the needs of hospitals.
Deficiencies are very rare.
But members of this donor network need to be renewed as they age and can no longer donate their blood.
But it is difficult to convince people to donate their blood, but above all to hold them back and encourage them to become a regular donor.
Because today’s life is so scary, we rarely find time to spend an hour donating her blood,” said Francine Décary.
With an annual budget of <0x24>297 million, Hema-Québec provides not only blood products, but also human tissue, including bone grafts, heart valves, eyeballs and skin that is used almost exclusively for large burns.
These tissues are analyzed, processed and frozen before being stored at Héma-Québec, which also manages the only public cord blood bank in Quebec.
The umbilical cord that was once considered a biomedical waste is full of blood rich in stem cells that can be used to treat serious diseases, such as leukemia.
“We celebrated, a few weeks ago, the banking of our thousandth sample of cord blood and we plan to collect more than a thousand of it every year.
We should start proposing it for transplants at the beginning of next year,” says Dr. Décary, describing this cord blood sampling program as very popular.
"Many mothers are disappointed that there is no access to it," because Hema-Québec does not have the means to offer this complex and expensive program in all hospitals in Quebec.
