The Psychology of Oversight: Why Do We Spend More Money?
When auctioning, buyers tend to spend more, and overestimate the merchandise.
Researchers in neurology and economics at the University of New York managed to update the neurological and economic bases of this known and seemingly irrational behavior.
According to their study published in the journal Science, humans don’t want to be distanced during this type of competition, such as an auction on eBay, and that’s why they even prefer to pay too high a price.
These researches have attempted to draw up a neurological scheme of this kind of "game" using experimental auction sales.
One group of volunteers played the lottery, while the other group participated in a game auction, while using a functional magnetic resonance imaging (MRI) method, the researchers analyzed the active brain areas of the experimental subjects.
In both games, participants could earn money, but during the auction of which an essential element is the overspending of a third, the set under the brain trunk, called the striatum, was put in intensive motion during the loss of the game.
This part of the brain, along with several other functions, plays a role in the mechanism of "self-stimulation" of the nervous system.
This is why, according to the researchers, the price rise is explained by the leak from the violent reaction of the striatum.
In support of their theories, the economists of this group of researchers pursued financial surveillance analyses.
During these, three groups overlisted in front of a partner, in various circumstances.
They simply informed the control group of the actual value of the product in question, and thus they made their bet.
To another group, they promised that if, in addition, they came out winning the game, then they would receive an additional <0x24>15, a reward.
While the third group received these <0x24>15 before the auction, the group members also lost that money, in case they lost the auction.
The difference between these two groups is in fact that the emphasis was placed in one on victory, while in the other, on failure.
By proving the neurologists' hypothesis, the players' team members were willing to make higher bets than those made by the control group and the victory group.
“These results cannot be demonstrated by any existing economic theory.
In fact, each of them explained the phenomena found during auctions only by the pleasure of winning and the parade in front of the risk.
Only neurological imaging methods have helped to eliminate the contradiction between the two theories by now leading to a third explanation." - Andrew Schotter, professor of economics at the University of New York.
Hepatitis: When Should We Consult a Doctor?
Worldwide, about half a billion people suffer from chronic hepatitis B or C, while in Hungary, chronic liver disease is mentioned among the leading causes of death.
It is estimated that there are 100 miles of hepatitis virus patients in Hungary, but only seven miles follow treatment, which is because patients often do not know that they are infected.
The name hepatitis is a generic name given to infections affecting the liver and caused by various viruses.
There are many similarities between their symptoms. Inflammation of the liver and jaundice are characteristic, but pathogens and diseases generated differ from each other.
Hepatitis viruses, according to the pathogenic genes, spread mainly in two forms: hepatitis A and E through the digestive tract (for example: contaminated food or water), hepatitis B, C, D and other viruses by blood and organic fluids (sperm, vaginal secretion, saliva).
For travelers, it is recommended to get vaccinated against viruses A and B. There is no vaccine against C.
Symptoms of hepatitis A appear two to three weeks after consuming contaminated foods, usually accompanied by a poor general condition, weakness, stomach aches and nausea.
Then a visible yellowing develops on the skin and on the white of the eye, the stools become clearer and the urine takes a darker color.
Worldwide, every year, one million people die from the most serious form of this disease, such as liver cancer or cirrhosis caused by hepatitis B.
The main cause of this is that, according to estimates, only one in ten patients receive medical treatment.
Hepatitis C can also have serious consequences: if not treated, it can lead to cirrhosis or liver cancer.
Most patients do not know that they are infected with the virus, because the pathogenic gene sullenly destroys liver cells. In many cases, the first symptoms appear only after 20-30 years.
Therefore, early prevention is very important, as well as regular screening tests.
Contamination is much higher than average among a population of three: people who had a blood transfusion before 1991, drug users and tattoos.
Currently, there are 200 million patients with chronic hepatitis C in the world.
Since the disease can be detected by a routine laboratory examination, it is advisable to consult your doctor treating as soon as symptoms of unknown origin are observed.
The disease can be cured, if detected in time. The virus can be eradicated from the body, in this way the risk of infection disappears and the development of cancer is prevented.
September 30 is World Hepatitis Day, organized for the first time in 2004 by organizations representing patients from all over the world.
Its goal is to draw attention to the chronic cirrhosis of the liver, caused by viruses, the causes of its development and the importance of early diagnosis of the disease.
