The British daily Telegraph published an article according to which researchers at the University of Oxford made an interesting experiment by analyzing how much faith in God can influence human pain tolerance.
As part of this experiment for the least bizarre, 12 Catholic believers and as many atheists were subjected to electroshocks, while each of them was observing a painting representing the Virgin Mary.
According to the results, Catholics were able to exclude much of the suffering.
Thanks to a human brain palpation technique, it was also found that Catholics were able to activate the part of their brain responsible for the regulation of pain.
This analysis is the first of a series of experiments, in which academics, scholars, philosophers and theologians participate from different sectors of the university.
Specifically, the experiment takes place as follows: an instrument emitting flashes and diffusing electroshocks is fixed on the left hand of the experimental subject.
The researchers asked the participants of the experiment to look sustainedly at two paintings, one being the Virgin Mary painted by Sassoferrato in the 17th century and the other, the Lady in the Hermine painted by Leonardo da Vinci in the 15th century.
The researchers at the origin of this experience hoped that the vision of the Virgin Mary evokes some kind of state of faith among believers, while the choice of Da Vinci’s painting, not very different from the first, was about its calming effect.
The experimental subjects spent half an hour in an MRI scanner, and during this time, received 20 electrochoques in four parts successively, while looking at either religious-themed or more general-themed painting.
Catholics said that in the sight of the Virgin Mary, they felt like "safe", like someone "cared for" and they "relaxed, and peace invaded them."
In view of the painting of religious themes, they saw 12% less pain than when they looked at Leonard’s work.
The psychologist Miguel Farias, who himself took part in the experiment, thinks that the same effects can be achieved with any other strong image, in atheists, provided they find the appropriate photo.
“We should find an image that they react very positively, such as a mother or a father,” the psychologist said.
Tom Wright, an Anglican bishop, welcomed the results of this research.
“The practice of faith should change and in many cases it actually changes our personality,” Wright added.
After these excellent results, the question remains of what would be the effect on the regulation of the pain of the subjects if the believers were shown a Madonna painted by Leonardo or by a painter of the same caliber?
Would the view of a better-quality Virgin Mary produce better results?
