The smart car mimics the burgundy’s flight
What method would be better to develop technologies capable of avoiding an obstacle, if it is not the imitation of an existing obstacle detector in nature?
Like the bees, for example.
In the amazing project presented at CEATEC, which took place in Japan, the donor bees gave Nissan engineers the strategic idea of starting to inspire them on how to design the next generation of obstacle detectors.
In collaboration with the University of Tokyo, Nissan has built a mini robot car, a bio-inspired self-roboting system, type BR23C, which it has equipped with bees qualities, the ultimate goal being to encourage the development of a system capable of avoiding all obstacles.
During its flights, each bee forms its own, oval-shaped space, which in reality looks a lot like our secure protective shell - explained, during the exhibition, Kazuhhiro Doi, the head of the brand's research and development department and technology public relations.
The bee’s faceted eye plays a key role, since it is able to see in all directions, at an angle of 300 degrees.
To mimic the functions of the eye with facets, engineers approached the idea of the laser telemeter.
It identifies the obstacles at an angle of 180 degrees and at a distance of 2 meters in front of the BR23C, it evaluates the distances and sends a signal to the on-board microprocessor, which immediately turns it into a avoidance maneuver.
The perception of the obstacle takes place in a fraction of a second. Then, the mini auto robot, imitating the movements of the bee, immediately changes the direction of its wheels by turning it at an angle sufficient to avoid collision.
Unlike any current system, this avoidance maneuver takes place entirely instinctively.
“If it weren’t, the mini auto robot wouldn’t be able to react quickly enough to avoid the obstacle,” said Toshiyuki Andoh, director of the Mobility Laboratory and the robotic car project.
It must react instinctively and instantly, since this technology corresponds to the most vulnerable and innermost layer of the protective envelope, a layer where the collision is currently considered inevitable.
All this process should reflect what the bee does to avoid the other bees.
The process must take place at a glance.
Unlike bees, the difference cannot go upwards, downwards or diagonally, it can only be two-dimensional, and only in the direction in which the wheels can rotate.
In this way, instead of the infinite combinations that bees possess to avoid other bees, in our case, we could only use rotary motion, acceleration as well as slowdown as maneuvers at the disposal of the mini auto robot.
The BR23C uses Lithium polymer batteries that are lighter and have a higher energy concentration, which makes their lifespan longer than in the Lithium-ion version.
According to Andoh, it’s the instinctive intelligent reaction that’s essential, not the processing of data, and even less the ability to store.
This mechanism should only process a few incoming signals per second, and react to them.
It is not necessary to store them and react with intuitive logic based on data from previous maneuvers. In this way, it uses only a few dozen kilobytes of memory continuously.
There is no need for memory with a capacity of giga-bytes, or even mega-bytes.
This is the first step towards designing an instantaneous avoidance technology, according to Nissan’s estimates, this system will make its entry into mass-produced cars in the next ten years.
Another application could be its incorporation into the GPS satellite navigation system, so that it can guide the driver to its destination by avoiding obstacles on its way.
