Industrial Prices Continued to Rise
In August 2008, domestic industrial sales prices increased by 0.1 per cent from the previous month, and by 12.9 per cent from August 2007, the Central Statistical Office of Hungary reported.
Industrial export sales prices increased by 1.1 per cent compared with those of July 2008, while compared to those of a year earlier, they decreased by 3.9 per cent.
As a result of fluctuations in domestic and export prices, industrial production prices increased by 0.7 per cent compared to the previous month, and by 3.2 per cent compared to the previous year.
Domestic industrial sales prices have only increased to a lesser extent: 0.1 per cent compared to the previous month.
Domestic sales prices in the manufacturing industry have only experienced a slight increase of 0.1 per cent compared to July.
In August 2008, the most significant price increase was observed in the leather and footwear manufacturing sector (2.8 per cent), with first the manufacture of bags and belts with a monthly increase of 4.6 per cent, then the production of footwear with a 2.5 per cent increase.
The higher price level of plastic and chemical raw materials has resulted in a significant monthly increase in prices in the manufacturing sector of chemicals and products (1.6 per cent).
This resulted in deflation in the oil processing sectors (1.4 per cent), the manufacture of electrical machinery and appliances (0.9 per cent), as well as a minimal increase in the wood processing sector (0.1 per cent).
The prices of paper production, publishing and printing activities have not changed.
The other sectors of the processing industry saw an increase of between 0.2 per cent and 0.9 per cent.
In the electricity, gas, steam and water supply sectors, representing a significant weight in the national industrial operation, prices rose by 0.3 per cent in August, mainly due to the effect of the increase in the price of gas set up by the authorities since 1st July.
In a 12-month comparison, taking into account domestic sales of the processing sectors, the oil processing sector prices experienced the most significant increase (32.4 per cent).
In the metallurgical manufacturing sector, prices increased by 13.2 per cent, while in the major food, beverage and tobacco sector, prices increased by 11 per cent.
Price reductions occurred in the textile and textile production sectors (2.5 per cent), as well as in the manufacture of electrical machinery and appliances (0.3 per cent).
In the other sectors of the processing industry, price increases ranged from 0.6 per cent to 9.1 per cent.
Over the entire processing industry, prices have increased by 10.2 percent over the past year.
Prices in the electricity, gas, steam and water supply sectors exceeded those of the previous year by 18.7 per cent.
Among the domestic trade groups and according to the sectoral allocation in August, the sectors initiating investment profits showed the most significant monthly price increases (0.7 per cent).
In the consumer goods production sectors, prices increased by 0.3 per cent, while those in the energy and materials-producing sectors for further processing did not change from the previous month.
In August 2008, compared to the same month of the previous year, there was the largest increase in the energy and materials sectors for further transformation (16.8 per cent).
In the consumer goods production sectors, inflation was measured at 6.8 per cent, while for the profit-initiating sectors, a decrease of 1.4 per cent.
Industrial export prices in HUF increased by 1.1 per cent in August compared to the previous month, while they fell by 3.9 per cent over 12 months.
In one month, our national means of payment weakened by 1.7 per cent against the euro, and by 7.1 per cent against the dollar. Compared to August 2007, it increased by 7.5 per cent against the euro and by 15.9 per cent against the dollar.
