The Nobel Prize in Economics to Paul Krugman.
The Nobel Prize in Economics was awarded to American Paul Krugman for his research on business models and the location of economic activities.
Krugman, 55, is a New-Keynesian who teaches at Princeton University and is also a famous New York Times editor.
Krugman is one of the top critics of the Bush administration's foreign policy and economic solutions.
A few months after the September 2001 attacks, during the days of Enron's bankruptcy, Krugman had written, in an article published in the New York Times, that the second event would have been more decisive than the first, in terms of consequences on U.S. history.
A prediction that sparked many controversies, and that was blamed to the economist for years, but now turned out to be accurate.
"I'm surprised and even a little shocked at the speed with which the memory of scandals like the collapse of Enron or Worldcom has vanished from the public's attention," Krugman said in late 2002.
According to Lorenzo Bini Smaghi, the Executive Committee of the European Central Bank, Krugman is a "high-value economist" but also a very aggressive, particularly critical disclosure of the Bush administration's excesses of liberalism.
